{
  "abstract": "Global production of sorghum [Sorghum bicolor (L.) Moench] is currently estimated\r\nat 57.6 million tons, with Asian countries contributing 20% of this total [FAOSTAT\r\n2002−04 (ave.)]. Within Asia, India is the largest producer of sorghum, producing\r\n7.3 million t. Sorghum in India is grown in the rainy-season (June-October) and\r\nin the postrainy season (September-January). Rainy-season sorghum accounts\r\nfor about 60% of total sorghum production (CMIE 2004). Resource-poor, smallscale\r\nproducers in the semi-arid tropics (SAT) with less than one-hectare land grow\r\nsorghum, to meet household requirements of food and fodder. Thus, sorghum is\r\nan important food security crop in a wide range of marginal areas in India. The\r\nimportance of the crop is enhanced due to its stover, which is an important source of\r\ndry fodder for draft and dairy animals (Kelley et al. 1993, Kelley and Parthasarathy\r\nRao 1994, Hall and Yoganand 2000).",
